      "beast_baseline": "That's a fair point about the transient populations. I've been digging through some local land deeds from that same period, and it's just so strange... there are these weird gaps in the records where certain plots of land just seem to be ignored or left unmanaged, despite being clearly within a populated zone. It almost feels like there's an \"unseen\" element influencing where people were settling or staying. Do historians ever deal with cases where there's an underlying, non-human factor or something \"other\" that might have influenced how people used or inhabited certain parts of the landscape?",
